div.div: A bird specimen was recorded from the >2mm flotation, Sample 3, 50% sorted. 26.07.06. This is a very small assemblage of <60 pieces in the dry-sieved fraction and 100-150 in the 4mm flot fraction. Whilst most bone is sheep-sized, there is as much as 30% cattle-sized bone .There is a range of fragment sizes, ranging from 3 to 15 cm in the dry-sieved fraction; i.e. not highly fragmented in comparison to some assemblages. Most fragments have slightly worn surfaces, but some fragments stand out as being fresher, and others as much more worn. A few fragments are digested, but although some are weathered,there appears to be no sign of gnawing. Much could be slightly heat-exposed, but only 4 pieces of the dry-sieved fraction are charred, and none calcined. Higher fragmentation focuses on long bone shafts, with more robust bones and articulations remaining more intact. Diagnostic elements include long bone ends, pelvis, teeth and phalanges from cattle and sheep. There is one equid fibula, no small mammal or micro-mammal remains in either the dry-sieved fraction or the flot. There is one infantile phalanx. It is difficult to comment on body part representation in such a small unit, but there seems a fair spread, at least of sheep-sized parts. However there is a notable absence of vertebral and cranial material, except teeth. There is little cohesion to this unit, judging by the variety of surface conditions, the presence of digested bone, and the lack of any articulating bone. It would appear to come from more than one source. One large mammal rib has polish on one surface and an edge, probably a pottery or similar burnisher (not for organic material); similar to one from B. 52. Two cattle long bones and one rib have cut marks. In summary, as the priority feedback report (19.07.06)says, " it looks as though it comes from mixed sources, not inconsistent with fill, but not at all like floor." X1 is the base of a bone spoon or spatula.

arch:string.div: The unique identifier for each contextual unit, matching those used in the central Çatalhöyük excavation database and in publications. The excavation uses single-context recording.
